Project: Investigating FBI Gun background Check System Data¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov.

  • The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file. It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type.

  • The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file. It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

Questions I will be focusing on answering:

  • How gun trends have changed across states?
  • Which features standout for states with highest gun sales?
  • Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?

Data Cleaning (Replace this with more specific notes!)¶

Gun data:¶

  1. Converting month to datetime and rename it to year-month
  2. Handling Nulls:
    • Columns with more than half their entries missing will be dropped
    • Premit recheck nulls were replaced by zero
    • Remaining columns nulls were replaced by their column's mean

Census data:¶

  1. Dropping duplicated rows
  2. Transforming Data so that there would be a column for feature, state and value
  3. Cleaning Fact column
    • Change "percent" to % sign
    • Split year if found
  4. Ensure correct datatypes are reflected

# 2- Manage NULLs, first i will drop columns with missing entries > row_count/2 ..i.e. more than half of the entries are missing

# I found help on how to do it here: 
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/31614804/how-to-delete-a-column-in-pandas-dataframe-based-on-a-condition

# however i modified it a little so that it is applied only from the 5th column onward
gun_df.drop(gun_df.iloc[:, 4:].columns[gun_df.iloc[:, 4:].apply(lambda col: col.isnull().sum() > gun_df.shape[0]/2)], 
            axis=1, inplace=True)

In [397]:
# we now investigate increase of gun registration per state
first_year_data = gun_df[gun_df['year-month']==min(gun_df['year-month'])][['state','totals']]
last_year_data = gun_df[gun_df['year-month']==max(gun_df['year-month'])][['state','totals']]


merged_data = pd.merge(last_year_data, first_year_data,  on='state')
merged_data['difference'] = merged_data['totals_x']-merged_data['totals_y']

merged_data.sort_values(by='difference', ascending=False, inplace=True)

# plot top 20 states which have the highest incearse in gun registration since first data entry till last date
merged_data.groupby(['state'])['difference'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)[0:20].plot(kind='bar',figsize=(20,10), color=(0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.6));
mp.suptitle('Top 20 States with highest difference in gun registration since start till end of this study', fontsize=18);
mp.xlabel('States', fontsize=14);
mp.ylabel('# of gun registration increase', fontsize=14)
mp.tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=12);

Conclusions¶

1- Data shows there is a growing rate of gun registration

2- Top states with either highest increase of gun registration/ownership are:

Gun Group: 'Kentucky', 'California', 'Texas', 'Illinois', 'Pennsylvania', 'Florida', 'Tennessee', 'Ohio', 'Indiana', 'Minnesota', 'Washington', 'Wisconsin', 'Virginia', 'Michigan', 'Missouri','Colorado', 'Georgia', 'North Carolina', 'Alabama', 'New York'

  • Gun Group falls within the least part of capita income, however they fall in the mid-range of total annual income of all states
  • Som of the Gun Group states falls within the least state with poverty%, however the majority of them falls within the top half of highest poverty%

3- After reviewing Education/Income/Age/Race censuses, there is an obvious remark; states seem to be divided into two groups, to clarify:

Group 1: New Mexico, New York, North Carolina, North Dakota, Ohio, California, Oregon, South Dakota, Tennesse, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Rhode Islands

Group 2: remaining states

  • Group 1 shows least propotion of Age/Racial/Composition/Poverty/Education compared to the remaining states

4- Limitations:

  • Data discrepencies in-term of collection data is definitely impacting the results.
  • Correlation between povery/education and population age and gun ownership would shed extra lights, but sadly this cannot be achieved using the datasets in hand.
  • Highlighting gun-group states within all-states charts would have been an excellent way to show where those states lie with respect to the rest, however I was not able to do that as I don't know how.
